The Effects of Stigmatization on Stress and Emotions

mel

2023-07-30

Does stigma function as a moderator in the relationship between perceived stress and emotional valence (positive or negative affect) experienced by individuals?

Perceived Stress (Continuous): (not stressed)1-5(very stressed) Emotional Valence(Continuous): (negative emotion)1-9(postive emotions) Condition (Categorical): condition 1: non stigamtized, 2= stigmatized

Predicted Results:

##Background:

#Research Question: Does stigma function as a moderator in the relationship between perceived stress and emotional valence (positive or negative affect) experienced by individuals?

#Study Design Perceived Stress: 1(not stressed)-5(very stressed) Outcome Variable Continuous:

Emotional Valence: 1(negative)-9(positive) Outcome Variable Continuous

Condition: condition 1:non-stigmatized, 2= stigmatized Predictor Variable Categorical

#Predicted Results: The interaction between perceived stress, stigma, and emotional valence is expected to be significant. Participants facing high stigma are predicted to have high perceived stress and lowest emotional valence (most negative affect) compared to other group.

Load Data

data <- read.csv("STGREW1b_comb.csv")

Reverse Code Perveived Stress

#recode 2 varibles Pss: Q2_2, Q2_3
data <- data %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(Q2_2, Q2_3), function(x){6-x})

Average and Create A Column for Percieved Stress

# make one col of pss/ average rows four items t create one single pss col
data <- data %>% 
  rowwise() %>% 
  mutate(PSS = mean(c_across(starts_with('Q2_')), na.rm = TRUE))

Format Condition to Catergorical

# condition col / get condition varibale in right format / need to be in factors (categorical)
data$Condition <- factor(data$Condition,
                          levels=c(1,2),
                          labels=c("Control","Stigma"))
data$Condition <- as.factor(data$Condition)

Descriptives of Condition

numeric_condition <- as.numeric(data$Condition)

if (any(is.na(numeric_condition)))
  stop("There are missing values in data$Condition. Please handle them before computing SD.")

c(summary(numeric_condition), "SD" = sd(numeric_condition))
##      Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max.        SD 
## 1.0000000 1.0000000 2.0000000 1.6436782 2.0000000 2.0000000 0.4816882

Descriptives of Emotional Valence

c(summary(data$mat_valence),"SD"=sd(data$mat_valence,na.rm=T))
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max.     NA's       SD 
## 1.000000 3.000000 5.000000 5.186047 7.000000 9.000000 1.000000 2.318781

Descriptives of Percieved Stress

c(summary(data$PSS),"SD"=sd(data$PSS,na.rm=T))
##      Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max.        SD 
## 1.2500000 2.2500000 2.7500000 2.7787356 3.2500000 4.5000000 0.7779906

Create a Linear Regression Model

# lm formula
model <- lm(mat_valence ~  Condition * PSS, data)

#see what output is
 summary (model)

Create Linear Regression Model Graph

plot <- ggplot(data, aes(x= PSS, y=mat_valence, color=Condition)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = T, alpha = .2) +
  labs(x="Perceived Stress", y="Emotional Valence")
